<br>
Walmart: Gross Margain = 22%<br>
             Operating Margain = 5%<br>
<br>
Target: Gross Margain = 31%<br>
           Operating Margain = 6%<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
First lets look at Gross Margain....(Sales - COGS)/Sales.  Its quite clear here whats going on.  First off, NO ONE gets lower prices from their vendors than Wal-Mart.  So what does this mean?  It means Target marks up their goods atleast 9% more than Wal-Mart (and thats assuming that Target gets the same prices as Wal-Mart which I guarantee you is not true...so its probably more like 10-11%).<br>
<br>
Now lets look at Operating Margains...(Sales - COGS - All Other Expenses (Besides Tax))/Sales...17% of Wal-Marts total sales goes towards paying other expenses (rent, power, wages).  25% of Targets sales goes towards the same thing.  Without digging into this farther, its hard to say which of Targets expenses are higher.  Its a good bet that Wal-Mart does indeed pay their workers less...not the full 8% less...but I'd be willing to be 3-5% less than Target.<br>
<br>
In the end, however, Target is still making more money per every dollar they take in that Wal-Mart.  So if you want to complain about Wal-Marts wages and keeping people at lower positions thats fine.  But if they raise wages, you can bet they'll follow Target's and the rest of the worlds business model and pass it on to the consumer...and guess what...Who shops at these stores the MOST...the low income families...and guess who works at Wal-Mart...the low income families.<br>
<br>
End Game...These low income families make $15 more at Wal-Mart because they raise wages 5% per hour and they spend $15 more at Wal-Mart each week.  <br>
<br>
Argument Over...unless you want to attack every single business in the United States.<br>
<br>
Matt<br>
