<br>
Reduction in cost per unit resulting from increased production, realized through operational efficiencies. Economies of scale can be accomplished because as production increases, the cost of producing each additional unit falls. <br>
<br>
<br>
Without Wal-Mart buying their CDs, it would cost the companies more money to produce their CDs.  Less CDs made = Less CDs to attribute fixed costs to.  (This is assuming you are right and that people can only buy their CDs from Wal-Mart and can't go to the store next door and buy the same CD.  If Wal-Mart didnt buy their CDs due to vulgarity and people couldn't buy CDs anywhere else...well then less CDs would be sold)<br>
<br>
If Wal-Mart was asking for say Mini-Disks instead of CDs, then you would have a economy of scale arguement.  Instead, they just have to select a different file to burn onto the CDs which costs the companies zero (or so little you might as well call in zero) in production.  The only costs come from the recording stage of the song in which verses are changed.  This is an increase in fixed costs.  The Record Labels benefit from Wal-Mart due to the economies of scale argument...not the other way around.  Their fixed costs, however, rise due to Wal-Mart, Clear Channel, MTV, Sporting Arenas, DJs, Moms who dont want their kids listening to music with bad words, etc etc.  So please boycott them as well.<br>
<br>
